It simply make testing easier, without changing the protection of existing 
code.
We find it sometimes easy to test part of a flow (which usually resides in 
a separate method) rather than
check the public interface function.

Also, I take the term &quot;public interface&quot; as relative. If an object exposes 
an interface (set of methods) to its peer objects within its package, I 
see no reason not to test it, even though those methods are 
package-protected.






&quot;Jason Rogers&quot; &lt;jason.rogers@...&gt;
